sec.p:
Research that starts out from the perspectives of actively and authentically listening to the lives, experiences and aspirations of young people and what works for them inside the learning process, has within it the scope to uncover the impediments, barriers and constraints that turn young people off school in droves. This is what is happening with the extant policy trajectories described above. On the other hand, by adopting approaches that actively listen to young lives, then you:


stand a chance of hearing the issues as they are existentially experienced by young people, rather than foreclosing this by purporting to have ‘solutions’, but which in effect amount to ‘problems’ that either do not exist, are foreclosed by predetermined answers, or else have no connection at all to what is actually happening;



develop ways of resolving issues that are likely to impede the learning of young people by integrally involving them from the outset, in articulating what the issues are, and navigating ways in which they will have a commitment to working out how to deal with matters in ways that give them a real modicum of ownership and the likelihood of a positive resolution;



embrace aspects of young lives that are seen as lying outside of school and that should be ‘parked’ at the school gate or classroom door, but which have a profound effect on learning, and instead dealing with them in open and mature rather than demeaning and punitive ways;



confront the burning issue of learning ‘relevance’ as seen from the vantage point of young people, and avoid the single most alienating factor that switches them off school, and instead, develop a meaningful curriculum and pedagogy that has a chance of captivating and engaging young people in wanting to learn.
